    "generation": "In Singapore, the penalties for individuals found guilty of money laundering can be quite severe. Under the Corruption, Drug Trafficking, and Other Serious Crimes (Confiscation of Benefits) Act (CDSA), the penalties can include:\n\n1. **Imprisonment**: Individuals can face up to 10 years in prison.\n2. **Fines**: There can be a fine of up to S$500,000, or in some cases, a fine of up to three times the value of the property involved in the money laundering.\n3. **Both Imprisonment and Fine**: In many cases, individuals can be sentenced to both imprisonment and a fine.\n\nAdditionally, the court can order the confiscation of any assets that are found to be the proceeds of crime. This means that any property or assets that were involved in or derived from the money laundering activities can be seized by the authorities.\n\nThe Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) and other regulatory bodies are very strict in enforcing these laws to maintain Singapore's reputation as a clean and corruption-free financial hub. If you have any specific concerns or need further details, it's always a good idea to consult a legal professional who specializes in these areas."
