    "generation": "In Singapore, the legal consequences of drug possession are extremely severe. Under the Misuse of Drugs Act, possession of any controlled drug is a serious offense. The penalties vary depending on the type and quantity of the drug involved.\n\nFor smaller quantities, possession can result in imprisonment, fines, or both. For example, possession of cannabis can lead to imprisonment of up to 10 years and a fine of up to S$20,000.\n\nHowever, if you are caught with larger quantities, the penalties become much more severe. For certain drugs, such as heroin or cocaine, possession of what is considered a \"trafficking\" quantity can lead to the mandatory death penalty. For example, possession of more than 15 grams of heroin or 30 grams of cocaine is considered trafficking and can result in the death penalty.\n\nIt's important to understand that Singapore takes a zero-tolerance approach to drug offenses. The government believes that strict laws and harsh penalties are necessary to protect the well-being of its citizens and maintain a safe and drug-free society.\n\nIf you or someone you know is struggling with drug addiction, there are resources available to help. The Singapore Anti-Narcotics Association (SANA) offers support and rehabilitation services. You can contact them at 1800-375-3762 for more information.\n\nRemember, the best way to avoid legal trouble and the severe consequences of drug possession is to stay away from drugs altogether."
