es in the investigation and prosecution of criminals.\n   - These agreements facilitate the extradition of suspects, the sharing of evidence, and the enforcement of court orders, ensuring that organized crime figures face justice regardless of their location.\n\n5. **Strategic Partnerships**:\n   - Singapore has strategic partnerships with international financial institutions and regulatory bodies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. For example, the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) works closely with the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures.\n   - These partnerships help us maintain a strong financial regulatory framework that deters organized crime groups from using Singapore as a base for their operations.\n\n6. **Anti-Gang Laws and Policies**:\n   - Singapore has stringent laws aimed at curbing organized crime, including the prohibition of gang signs and symbols, and heavy penalties for gang-related activities. The Criminal Law (Temporary Provisions) Act (CLA) allows for the detention of suspected gang members without trial for up to two years, renewable if deemed necessary.\n   - International collaborations help enforce these laws by providing additional resources and expertise. For instance, intelligence from foreign agencies can be crucial in identifying and dismantling international gangs operating in Singapore.\n\nIn summary, international collaborations are essential for Singapore's efforts to combat organized crime. By leveraging the strengths and resources of our global partners, we can effectively address the complex and evolving nature of transnational criminal activities."
