he country's AML/CFT framework. It receives, analyzes, and disseminates suspicious transaction reports from financial institutions and other reporting entities.\n   - The STRO collaborates with international FIUs to share information and intelligence, enhancing the effectiveness of global AML efforts.\n\n3. **Legislation and Regulations:**\n   - Singapore has robust legislation, such as the Corruption, Drug Trafficking and Other Serious Crimes (Confiscation of Benefits) Act (CDSA) and the Anti-Money Laundering and Countering the Financing of Terrorism Act (AMLCFTA), which provide the legal framework for combating financial crimes.\n   - The MAS also issues regular advisories and guidelines to financial institutions, helping them stay updated on the latest AML/CFT risks and best practices.\n\n4. **International Engagement:**\n   - Singapore actively participates in international organizations like the FATF and the Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG). It contributes to the development of global AML/CFT standards and best practices.\n   - The country hosts international conferences and training programs to enhance regional cooperation and capacity building in AML/CFT.\n\n5. **Technology and Innovation:**\n   - Singapore is at the forefront of leveraging technology to combat financial crimes. The MAS encourages the use of advanced analytics, artificial intelligence, and blockchain technology to detect and prevent money laundering and other financial crimes.\n   - The Singapore FinTech Association and other industry bodies also promote innovation in AML/CFT solutions.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nInternational cooperation and information sharing are essential tools in the fight against global money laundering and financial crimes. Singapore, through its robust regulatory framework, active international engagement, and technological innovation, plays a significant role in these efforts. By working closely with global partners, Singapore contributes to a safer and more se