    "topic": "Terrorism",
    "question": "What are the key legislative measures in Singapore aimed at preventing terrorism?",
    "generation": "In Singapore, one of the key legislative measures aimed at preventing terrorism is the **Internal Security Act (ISA)**. The ISA was enacted in 1960 and gives the government broad powers to detain individuals without trial if they are suspected of activities that threaten national security, including terrorism. This act allows for preventive detention and the imposition of restrictions on individuals to stop them from engaging in such activities.\n\nAnother important legislative measure is the **Terrorism (Suppression of Financing) Act (TSOFA)**, which was introduced in 2002. TSOFA is designed to prevent the financing of terrorist activities and organizations. It empowers the authorities to freeze assets and funds of suspected terrorists and to impose penalties on those who engage in or facilitate the financing of terrorism.\n\nAdditionally, the **Public Order Act** (POA) of 2009 plays a crucial role in maintaining public order and safety by regulating assemblies and processions, and it can be used to prevent activities that may lead to public disorder or be linked to terrorism.\n\nThese laws work in conjunction with the **SGSecure** campaign, which is a national movement to strengthen community preparedness and resilience against terrorism. SGSecure aims to educate and empower Singaporeans to take proactive steps in preventing and responding to terrorist threats."
