Singaporean officials and helps in the repatriation of victims.\n\n5. **Interpol**:\n   - Through Interpol, Singapore shares intelligence and coordinates operations with law enforcement agencies worldwide to track and apprehend traffickers.\n\n### Domestic Efforts\n1. **Anti-Trafficking Taskforce**:\n   - Singapore has an inter-agency taskforce comprising various government agencies, including the Ministry of Home Affairs (MHA), Ministry of Manpower (MOM), and the Attorney-General’s Chambers (AGC). This taskforce ensures a coordinated and multi-faceted approach to combating human trafficking.\n\n2. **Legislation**:\n   - The Prevention of Human Trafficking Act (PHTA) was enacted in 2015 to provide a legal framework for the prevention, investigation, prosecution, and punishment of human trafficking offenses. The PHTA also includes provisions for victim protection and support.\n\n3. **Victim Support**:\n   - Singapore has established shelters and support services for victims of trafficking. These services include healthcare, counseling, and legal assistance. The government also works with non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to provide comprehensive care.\n\n4. **Public Awareness**:\n   - The government runs awareness campaigns to educate the public about the signs of human trafficking and how to report suspected cases. If you suspect any signs of trafficking, you can call the Anti-Human Trafficking Hotline at 9789 0000 for immediate assistance.\n\n### Key International Agreements\n- **United Nations Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children**: This protocol sets out the definition of human trafficking and outlines measures to prevent it, protect victims, and promote cooperation among countries.\n- **ASEAN Convention Against Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children (ACTIP)**: This convention, adopted in 2015, is a regional agreement that commits ASEAN member states to combat human trafficking through preventive measures, protection of victims, and prosecution of offenders.\n- **Bali Process**: This non-binding forum facilitates regional cooperation in addressing human trafficking, smuggling, and related transnational crimes.\n\nBy leveraging these international collaborations and adhering to global standards, Singapore aims to create a safer environment for all and to eradicate human trafficking. If you have any more specific questions or need further information, feel free to ask!"
